{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> δαίμων</b>, ονος, <br /> <i>vocative</i> δαίμων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1480 (Lyric poetry), δαῖμον 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 2.11 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], ὁ, ἡ, <b>god, goddess,</b> of individual gods or goddesses, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.222, 3.420, etc.; δαίμονι ἶσος 5.438 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἐμίσγετο δαίμονι δαίμων, of Φιλίη and Νεῖκος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus 59.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—but more frequently of <b>the Divine power</b> (while θεός denotes a God in person), <b>the Deity,</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.27 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; πρὸς δαίμονα against <b>the Divine power,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.98; σὺν δαίμονι by its grace, 11.792 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κατὰ δαίμονα, almost, ={τύχῃ}, by <b>chance,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.111; τύχᾳ δαίμονος 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 8.67 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἄμαχος δ., i. e. Destiny, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus 15.23: in _plural_, ὅτι δαίμονες θέλωσιν,\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] what <b>the Gods</b> ordain, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 16.117; ταῦτα δ᾽ ἐν τῷ δ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1443; ἡ τύχη καὶ ὁ δ. 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 13.63, compare 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 3.111; κατὰ δαίμονα καὶ συντυχίαν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 544. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>the power controlling the destiny of individuals</b>: hence, one's <b>lot</b> or <b>forlune,</b> δτυγερὸς δέ οἱ ἔχραε δ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.396, compare 10.64; δαίμονος αἶσα κακή 11.61 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; δαίμονα δώσω I will deal thee <b>fate,</b> i.e. kill thee, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"I 1.8.166 \">Refs</a>]; frequently in Trag. of <b>good</b> or <b>ill fortune,</b> ὅταν ὁ δ. εὐροῇ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 601; δ. ἀσινής [prev. author] “Ag.” 1342 (Lyric poetry); κοινός [prev. author] “Th.” 812; γενναῖος πλὴν τοῦ δαίμονος 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 76; δαίμονος σκληρότης 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 3.3.4; τὸν οἴακα στρέφει δ. ἑκάστῳ 4th c.BC: Anaxandrides Comicus 4.6 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; personified as <b>the good</b> or <b>evil genius</b> of a family or person, δ. τῷπλεισθενιδῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1569, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1194 (Lyric poetry); ὁ ἑκάστου δ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 107d, compare “PMag.Lond.” 121.505, 4th c.AD: Iamblichus Philosophus “de Mysteriis” 9.1; ὁ δ. ὁ τὴν ἡμετέραν μοῖραν λελογχώς 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 2.78; ἅπαντι δ. ἀνδρι συμπαρίσταται εὐθὺς γενομένῳ μυσταγωγὸς τοῦ βίου 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus 16.2 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator; δ. ἀλάστορες [prev. author] 8D.; ὁ μέγας [τοῦ Καίσαρος] δ. 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Caesar” 69; ὁ σὸς δ. κακός [prev. passage]; ὁ βασιλέως δ. [prev. author] “Art.” 15; ἦθος ἀνθρώπῳ δ. 1st c.AD(?): Heraclitus 119; Ξενοκράτης φησὶ τὴν ψυχὴν ἑκάστου εἶναι δ. 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Topica” 112a37. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> δαίμονες, οἱ, <b>souls of men of the golden age,</b> acting as tutelary deities, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 122, 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 1348, 6th c.BC: Phocylides Lyricus 15, 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus 115.5, etc.; θεῶν, δ., ἡρώων, τῶν ἐν Ἅιδου 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 392a: less frequently in _sing._, δαίμονι δ᾽ οἷος ἔησθα τὸ ἐργάζεσθαι ἄμεινον 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 314 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τὸν τὲ δ. Δαρεῖον ἀγκαλεῖσθε, of the deified Darius, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Persae” 620 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; νῦν δ᾽ ἐστὶ μάκαιρα δ., of Alcestis, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Alcestis” 1003 (Lyric poetry), compare “IG” 12(5).305.5 (from Paros)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: later, of <b>departed souls,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Luct.” 24 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; δαίμοσιν εὐσεβέσιν, = <b>Dis Manibus,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Inscriptiones Graecae 14.1683\">Refs</a>]; so θεοὶ δ., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work]938, +others: also, \">Refs</a>]<b>ghost,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 6.6.8. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> generally, <b>spiritual</b> or <b>semi-divine being</b> inferior to the Gods, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.415a, +others, 4th c.AD: Sallustius Philosophus 12, 5th-6th c.AD: Damascius Philosophus “de Principiis” 183, etc.\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; especially <b>evil spirit, demon,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"NT.Matt.8.31, 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Antiquitates Judaicae” 8.2.5; φαῦλοι δ. 3rd c.AD: Alexander Aphrodisiensis Philosophus “Problemata - Physici et Medici Graeci Minores” 2.46 \">NT+1st c.AD+</a>]; δαίμονος ἔσοδος εἰς τὸν ἄνθρωπον, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Aretaeus Medicus “περὶ αἰτιῶν καὶ σημείων χρονίων παθῶν” 1.4; πρᾶξις ἐκβάλλουσα δαίμονας “PMag.Par.” 1227. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> ἀγαθὸς δ. <b>the Good Genius</b> to whom a toast was drunk after dinner, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 525, 4th c.BC: Nicostratus Comicus 20, 1st c.BC: Diodorus Siculus Historicus 4.3, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.655e, 5th c.BC: Philonides Comicus cited in 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 15.675b, 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 9.39.5, “IG” 12(3).436 (from Thera)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], etc.; of Nero, ἀ. δ. τῆς οἰκουμένης [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “OGI” 666.3 \">Refs</a>]; of the Nile, ἀ. δ. ποταμός[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work]672.7 (1st c.AD) \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; of the tutelary genius of individuals (above 1), ἀ. δ. Ποσειδωνίου [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “SIG” 1044.9 (Halic.): _plural_, δαίμονες ἀ.,\">Refs</a>] = Latin <i>Di Manes</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “SIG” 1246 (from Mylasa): Astrology texts, ἀγαθός, κακός δ., names of celestial κλῆροι, 4th c.AD: Paulus Alexandrinus Astrologus “N.” 4, “O.” 1, etc. (Less correctly written Ἀγαθοδαίμων, which see). \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> ={δαήμων}, <b>knowing,</b> δ. μάχης <b>skilled in</b> fight, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th c.BC: Archilochus Lyricus 3.4. (5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Cratylus” 398b \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>], suggests this as the originally sense; while others would write δαήμονες in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th c.BC: Archilochus Lyricus \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>], and get rid of this sense altogether; compare however αἵμων. More probably the Root of δαίμων (<b>deity</b>) is δαίω <b>to distribute destinies;</b>;[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare 7th c.BC: Alcman Lyricus 48.) \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G1142","accentedUnicode":"δαίμων","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G1139","matchingForm":"δαιμονίζομαι","stepTransliteration":"daimonizomai","gloss":"be demonised","_zh_tw_Gloss":"被鬼附","_es_Gloss":"estar endemoniado ","_zh_Gloss":"被鬼附"},{"strongNumber":"G1140","matchingForm":"δαιμόνιον","step